 well in his person wrought\nTo be set high in place, we did commend\nTo your remembrances: but you have found,\nScaling his present bearing with his past,\nThat he's your fixed enemy, and revoke\nYour sudden approbation.\nTo the Capitol, come:\nWe will be there before the stream o' the people;\nAnd this shall seem, as partly 'tis, their own,\nWhich we have goaded onward.\nPass no further.\nStop,\nOr all will fall in broil.\nYou show too much of that\nFor which the people stir: if you will pass\nTo where you are bound, you must inquire your way,\nWhich you are out of, with a gentler spirit,\nOr never be so noble as a consul,\nNor yoke with him for tribune.\n'Twere well\nWe let the people know't.\nIt is a mind\nThat shall remain a poison where it is,\nNot poison any further.\nHas spoken like a traitor, and shall answer\nAs traitors do.\nThis a consul? no.\nGo, call the people:\nin whose name myself\nAttach thee as a traitorous innovator,\nA foe to the public weal: obey, I charge thee,\nAnd follow to thine answer.\nHelp, ye citizens!\nHere's he that would take from you all your power.\nHear me, people; peace!\nYou are at point to lose your liberties:\nCORIOLANUS would have all from you; CORIOLANUS,\nWhom late you have named for consul.\nWhat is the city but the people?\nThis deserves death.\nTherefore lay hold of him;\nBear him to the rock Tarpeian, and from thence\nInto destruction cast him.\nWhere is this viper\nThat would depopulate the city and\nBe every man himself?\nHe shall be thrown down the Tarpeian rock\nWith rigorous hands: he hath resisted law,\nAnd therefore law shall scorn him further trial\nThan the severity of the public power\nWhich he so sets at nought.\nPeace!\nSir, how comes't that you\nHave holp to make this rescue?\nConsul! what consul?\nSpeak briefly then;\nFor we are peremptory to dispatch\nThis viperous traitor: to eject him hence\nWere but one danger, and to keep him here\nOur certain death: therefore it is decreed\nHe dies to-night.\nHe's a disease that must be cut away.\nThis is clean kam.\nWhat do ye talk?\nHave we not had a taste of his obedience?\nOur aediles smote? ourselves resisted? Come.\nNoble Menenius,\nBe you then as the people's officer.\nMasters, lay down your weapons.\nMeet on the market-place. We'll attend you there:\nWhere, if you bring not CORIOLANUS, we'll proceed\nIn our first way.\nHave you a catalogue\nOf all the voices that we have procured\nSet down by the poll?\nHave you collected them by tribes?\nAssemble presently the people hither;\nAnd when they bear me say 'It shall be so\nI' the right and strength o' the commons,' be it either\nFor death, for fine, or banishment, then let them\nIf I say fine, cry 'Fine;' if death, cry 'Death.'\nInsisting on the old prerogative\nAnd power i' the truth o' the cause.\nMake them be strong and ready for this hint,\nWhen we shall hap to give 't them.\nWell, here he comes.\nDraw near, ye people.\nI do demand,\nIf you submit you to the people's voices,\nAllow their officers and are content\nTo suffer lawful censure for such faults\nAs shall be proved upon you?\nAnswer to us.\nWe charge you, that you have contrived to take\nFrom Rome all season'd office and to wind\nYourself into a power tyrannical;\nFor which you are a traitor to the people.\nMark you this, people?\nPeace!\nWe need not put new matter to his charge:\nWhat you have seen him do and heard him speak,\nBeating your officers, cursing yourselves,\nOpposing laws with strokes and here defying\nThose whose great power must try him; even this,\nSo criminal and in such capital kind,\nDeserves the extremest death.\nFor that he has,\nAs much as in him lies, from time to time\nEnvied against the people, seeking means\nTo pluck away their power, as now at last\nGiven hostile strokes, and that not in the presence\nOf dreaded justice, but on the ministers\nThat do distribute it; in the name o' the people\nAnd in the power of us the tribunes, we,\nEven from this instant, banish him our city,\nIn peril of precipitation\nFrom off the rock Tarpeian never more\nTo enter our Rome gates: i' the people's name,\nI say it shall be so.\nHe's sentenced; no more hearing.\nWe know your drift: speak what?\nGo, see him out at gates, and follow him,\nAs he hath followed you, with all despite;\nGive him deserved vexation. Let a guard\nAttend us through the city.\nBid them all home; he's gone, and we'll no further.\nThe nobility are vex'd, whom we see have sided\nIn his behalf.\nBid them home:\nSay their great enemy is gone, and they\nStand in their ancient strength.\nLet's not meet her.\nThey say she's mad.\nAre you mankind?\nO blessed heavens!\nWhat then?\nI would he had continued to his country\nAs he began, and not unknit himself\nThe noble knot he made.\nWhy stay we to be baited\nWith one that wants her wits?\nWe hear not of him, neither need we fear him;\nHis remedies are tame i' the present peace\nAnd quietness of the people, which before\nWere in wild hurry. Here do we make his friends\nBlush that the world goes well, who rather had,\nThough they themselves did suffer by't, behold\nDissentious numbers pestering streets than see\nOur tradesmen with in their shops and going\nAbout their functions friendly.\n'Tis he,'tis he: O, he is grown most kind of late.\nYour Coriolanus\nIs not much miss'd, but with his friends:\nThe commonwealth doth stand, and so would do,\nWere he more angry at it.\nWhere is he, hear you?\nGod-den, our neighbours.\nLive, and thrive!\nThis is a happier and more comely time\nThan when these fellows ran about the streets,\nCrying confusion.\nAnd affecting one sole throne,\nWithout assistance.\nWe should by this, to all our lamentation,\nIf he had gone forth consul, found it so.\nCome, what talk you\nOf CORIOLANUS?\nTell not me:\nI know this cannot be.\n'Tis this slave;\xe2\x80\x94\nGo whip him, 'fore the people's eyes:\xe2\x80\x94his raising;\nNothing but his report.\nWhat more fearful?\nThis is most likely!\nThe very trick on't.\nGo, masters, get you 