nlikes. 'Tis a commodity will lose the gloss with\nlying; the longer kept, the less worth: off with 't\nwhile 'tis vendible; answer the time of request.\nVirginity, like an old courtier, wears her cap out\nof fashion: richly suited, but unsuitable: just\nlike the brooch and the tooth-pick, which wear not\nnow. Your date is better in your pie and your\nporridge than in your cheek; and your virginity,\nyour old virginity, is like one of our French\nwithered pears, it looks ill, it eats drily; marry,\n'tis a withered pear; it was formerly better;\nmarry, yet 'tis a withered pear: will you anything with it?\nWhat one, i' faith?\nWhat's pity?\nLittle Helen, farewell; if I can remember thee, I\nwill think of thee at court.\nUnder Mars, I.\nWhy under Mars?\nWhen he was predominant.\nWhy think you so?\nThat's for advantage.\nI am so full of businesses, I cannot answer thee\nacutely. I will return perfect courtier; in the\nwhich, my instruction shall serve to naturalize\nthee, so thou wilt be capable of a courtier's\ncounsel and understand what advice shall thrust upon\nthee; else thou diest in thine unthankfulness, and\nthine ignorance makes thee away: farewell. When\nthou hast leisure, say thy prayers; when thou hast\nnone, remember thy friends; get thee a good husband,\nand use him as he uses thee; so, farewell.\n'Tis not his fault, the spark.\nMost admirable: I have seen those wars.\nAn thy mind stand to't, boy, steal away bravely.\nCommit it, count.\nNoble heroes, my sword and yours are kin. Good\nsparks and lustrous, a word, good metals: you shall\nfind in the regiment of the Spinii one Captain\nSpurio, with his cicatrice, an emblem of war, here\non his sinister cheek; it was this very sword\nentrenched it: say to him, I live; and observe his\nreports for me.\nMars dote on you for his novices! what will ye do?\nUse a more spacious ceremony to the\nnoble lords; you have restrained yourself within the\nlist of too cold an adieu: be more expressive to\nthem: for they wear themselves in the cap of the\ntime, there do muster true gait, eat, speak, and\nmove under the influence of the most received star;\nand though the devil lead the measure, such are to\nbe followed: after them, and take a more dilated farewell.\nWorthy fellows; and like to prove most sinewy sword-men.\nWhy, 'tis the rarest argument of wonder that hath\nshot out in our latter times.\nSo I say.\nSo I say.\nRight; so I say.\nWhy, there 'tis; so say I too.\nRight; as 'twere, a man assured of a\xe2\x80\x94\nJust, you say well; so would I have said.\nIt is, indeed: if you will have it in showing, you\nshall read it in\xe2\x80\x94what do you call there?\nThat's it; I would have said the very same.\nNay, 'tis strange, 'tis very strange, that is the\nbrief and the tedious of it; and he's of a most\nfacinerious spirit that will not acknowledge it to be the\xe2\x80\x94\nAy, so I say.\nI would have said it; you say well. Here comes the king.\nMort du vinaigre! is not this Helen?\nYour pleasure, sir?\nRecantation! My lord! my master!\nA most harsh one, and not to be understood without\nbloody succeeding. My master!\nTo any count, to all counts, to what is man.\nYou are too old, sir; let it satisfy you, you are too old.\nWhat I dare too well do, I dare not do.\nHadst thou not the privilege of antiquity upon thee,\xe2\x80\x94\nMy lord, you give me most egregious indignity.\nI have not, my lord, deserved it.\nWell, I shall be wiser.\nMy lord, you do me most insupportable vexation.\nWell, thou hast a son shall take this disgrace off\nme; scurvy, old, filthy, scurvy lord! Well, I must\nbe patient; there is no fettering of authority.\nI'll beat him, by my life, if I can meet him with\nany convenience, an he were double and double a\nlord. I'll have no more pity of his age than I\nwould of\xe2\x80\x94I'll beat him, an if I could but meet him again.\nI most unfeignedly beseech your lordship to make\nsome reservation of your wrongs: he is my good\nlord: whom I serve above is my master.\n